There are 25 OCTs currently listed in the annex II of the TFEU. Their associated territories status was created under the Treaty of Rome in 1957, and is defined as the territories which have special relations with Denmark, France, the Netherlands and the United Kingdom.&#xd;
&#xd;
Out of 25 OCTs, all the permanently inhabited territories (21) are members of OCTA:&#xd;
&#xd;
- Anguilla&#xd;
- Aruba&#xd;
- Bermuda&#xd;
- Bonaire&#xd;
- British Virgin Islands&#xd;
- Cayman Islands&#xd;
- Curaçao&#xd;
- Falkland Islands&#xd;
- Greenland&#xd;
- Montserrat&#xd;
- New Caledonia&#xd;
- French Polynesia&#xd;
- Saba&#xd;
- Saint Barthélemy&#xd;
- Saint Pierre and Miquelon&#xd;
- Sint Eustatius&#xd;
- Sint Maarten&#xd;
- Pitcairn&#xd;
- Saint Helena&#xd;
- Turks &amp; Caicos Islands&#xd;
- Wallis and Futuna&#xd;
&#xd;
As well as the French Southern Antarctic Lands - TAAF.
